One of my patients sent me this video from @jillianmichaels about the new drug semaglutide. She has a gross misunderstanding of obesity and why people fail to lose weight along with how these trials are run.

I forgot to add in a quick segment about the fear of thyroid cancer. It is a very rare type of thyroid cancer that rats are predisposed to. There is no signal that this occurs in humans.

I have many patients on this medicine who finally feel they have a normal appetite. It’s not that they lack willpower, it’s because it’s physiology! Let me know what you think of the video.

node.text:
I’ve noticed more and more of these folks popping up. They lean on their school or where they are affiliated to push their pseudoscience. It’s unfortunate because we all hold these institutions in high regard.

Credentials and affiliations increase the odds someone probably knows what they are talking about but it doesn’t guarantee it. Some people are even taking advantage of it.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Spencer Nadolsky on July 17, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says '@DrNadolsKy 1.Carbs aren't inherently fattening. 2. Same with artificial sweeteners. 3. Fasting isn't magical. Stop buying stupid detoxes. 5. Consistency trumps all.'.

node.text:
Just a reminder!

Carbohydrates are not inherently fattening. This has been studied over and over again. It’s true that highly refined ultra processed foods containing carbohydrates (and fat) are easily over eaten. But carbs come in different packages. Think strawberries. Think legumes. Don’t think donuts snd cookies, which aren’t satiating and also contain fat (high calorie).

I’ve talked about artificial sweeteners many times before. They are also not fattening. Anyone who says this doesn’t have a clue.

Fasting helps people lose weight because they eat less. They literally aren’t eating. The proposed magic from fasting for weight loss doesn’t exist.

Detox drinks are stupid. Not much else needed to say.

When it comes to diet success, the most important aspect is adherence or how consistent they are with the dietary recommendations (as long as those recommendations follow the principles of energy balance - calories in vs out). Trying to be perfect may lead to complete burnout and quitting. Instead shoot for 80-90% and you’ll be fine. ❤️

I made this a few years ago. I think it’s interesting to see how the same portions can look differently depending on what you put it in or on. Some of the research that went into this has been questioned however I hope it is replicated. It’s possible there is an affect of how much we eat due to our visualization depending on what we put our food in on.

For example using a salad plate with the same amount of food may have an effect of eating less compared to using a large dinner plate.

New weight loss books come out each week.

If they claim you don’t have to eat fewer calories to lose weight, don’t buy it. They will then go on to find a way to help you eat less while saying it’s your hormones.

If a weight loss book is truthful, it will say straight up that energy balance matters, but that there are strategies to do it without feeling as much like you’re dieting. Key difference.

Sorry there is no magic folks! ❤️❤️

node.text:
A ketogenic diet can be therapeutic for a few conditions. It’s not keto that I dislike, it’s the idiot gurus who just make up stuff.

I’m not sure how anyone takes someone who says fruit is bad for you seriously. It’s fricking fruit.

Bacon is not and will never be a health food. Of course it tastes good. I don’t think it’s horrible for you either. But I wouldn’t glorify it!

Ldl cholesterol can increase due to multiple mechanisms on keto (low polyunsaturated fat, high saturated fat, low soluble fiber, very low insulin levels). Sometimes cholesterol levels go as high or even higher than someone with genetic causes. It’s very clear that those with genetic causes have much higher rates of cardiovascular disease. We are actually studying what happens in healthy keto folks with high cholesterol now. I wouldn’t ever recommend not worrying about your ldl cholesterol!

Anyway, when I have patients do keto, I have them focus on less processed meats while getting fat from nuts, avocados, and olive oil and get as many plants as possible without coming out of ketosis (if the ketones even help the individual for appetite since I’m mostly doing it for obesity and type 2 diabetes).

Some folks are very strict during the week snd then completely let go on the weekend. You can certainly have some of these things when accounting for average energy balance over the week, but it can be easy to go overboard. ❤️❤️
